      "text": "Our programs were assembled out of simple processes that shared synchronous access to an I/O space. Jeff Bradford built a LED display that could capture one byte of that space for debugging purposes."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "505abde209fd58b8",
      "text": "Dozens of I/O address were statically allocated to standard processes that were frequently reused components of our programs."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "006d34c204d117da",
      "text": "Processes would write to their allocated I/O port on every significant state change. Typical states were: waiting for input, computing, waiting to write output, and allocating memory."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "c1307de17d6483b4",
      "text": "Processes would encode their state using a 1-of-8 code so that only one LED would be on at any given time."
